english:
  title: Record of the Reporting Clepsydra Pavilion
  author: Kim Dun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    His Majesty commanded that the ancient water clock, lacking precision, be remade. Four water-distribution vessels were cast, differing in size, along with two receiving vessels to be alternated as water was transferred. The main cylinder measured eleven feet two inches in length with a diameter of one foot eight inches. Two indicator rods, ten feet two inches long, marked the twelve hours upon their face, each hour divided into eight intervals, which together with the remainder fractions comprised one hundred marks, each mark further divided into twelve parts. The former night rod, divided into twenty-one segments, proved cumbersome in alternation; now, following the Calendar of Granted Times and calibrating day and night by rising and falling, approximately every two solar terms corresponded to one rod segment, yielding twelve rods total that, when cross-checked against the Simplified Celestial Instrument, erred not by a hair's breadth.

    His Majesty, fearing that those announcing time might fall into error, commanded the Guard General, Minister Chang Yong-shil, to fashion wooden automata to announce the hours of themselves, dispensing with human labor. The mechanism was first built as a three-chambered pavilion. Within the eastern chamber, two-tiered seating was arranged: upon the upper tier stood three deities—one governing the hours and striking the bell, one governing the watches and striking the drum, one governing the marks and striking the gong. Below the middle tier, a rotating wheel was installed bearing twelve deities in sequence, each fashioned with iron frames capable of ascending and descending, each holding a time tablet and taking turns announcing the hours.

    The mechanism's ingenious working was housed within the central chamber: a tower held the distributing vessels above and receiving vessels below. Upon the receiving vessel rose a wooden frame, hollow within and empty-faced, measuring eleven feet four inches in length, six inches wide, eight-tenths of an inch thick, and four inches deep. Within the hollow was a partition set back one inch from the face. On the left was mounted a bronze plate, aligned with the indicator rod, two inches wide, its surface pierced with twelve holes to receive small bronze balls the size of pellets, each hole fitted with a mechanism to open and close, governing the twelve hours. On the right was mounted another bronze plate, similarly aligned, two and one-half inches wide, its surface pierced with twenty-five holes to receive small bronze balls like those on the left plate, governing the twelve rod segments. Twelve such plates were rotated according to the seasons to govern the watches and marks.

    The floating indicator rod in the receiving vessel bore at its head a horizontal iron piece like a chopstick, four and one-half inches long. Before the vessel lay a depression wherein was obliquely set a bronze plate, its front end meeting the bottom of the hollow wooden frame, its rear end extending beneath the eastern chamber's seating. Four partitions were arranged in angular-passage formation, upon which sat large iron balls the size of eggs—the left twelve governing hours, the middle five governing watches and initial marks, the right twenty governing marks. At each ball's position hung rings for opening and closing, with a horizontal mechanism resembling a spoon: one end curved to hook the ring, the other end round to receive the ball, both connected at the waist by a round axle allowing up-and-down motion, with the round end meeting the holes of bronze tubes.

    Two bronze tubes were obliquely set upon the partitions: the left, four feet five inches long with a diameter of one and one-half inches, governing hours with twelve holes in its lower face; the right, eight feet long with the same diameter, governing marks with twenty-five holes in its lower face. All holes were fitted with mechanisms initially opened fully; when a small bronze ball from the plate fell and moved the mechanism, it would automatically close that hole while opening the path for the next ball to roll through.

    Beneath the upper tier of the eastern chamber's seating: on the left hung two short tubes, one receiving balls and one containing a mechanism-spoon with its round end protruding halfway to meet the bottom of the receiving tube. On the right stood two each of round and square columns, the round columns hollow with spoon-like mechanisms inside, half-protruding and half-retracting, with five on the left and ten on the right. Square columns obliquely threaded through small tubes, four to each column, one end fashioned as a lotus leaf, the other as a dragon's mouth—the lotus leaf receiving the ball, the dragon's mouth discharging it, with dragon's mouth and lotus leaf vertically aligned. Above these hung two more short tubes, one receiving watch-balls and one receiving mark-balls.

    On the right square columns, each lotus leaf had two vertical short tubes and one horizontal short tube attached below; the horizontal tube's end connected to the lotus leaf below on the left square column. The five spoon-mechanisms of the left round column and five of the right had their round ends meeting between dragon's mouth and lotus leaf. The five spoon-mechanisms of the right round column had their round ends half-entering the interior of the vertical tubes.

    As water dripped into the receiving vessel, the floating indicator rod gradually rose, pressing the left bronze plate's hole-mechanism at the proper time. The small ball would fall, roll into the bronze tube, drop through the hole while pressing its mechanism—then the mechanism opened and a large ball fell, rolling into the suspended short tube below the seating. Falling further, it moved the mechanism-spoon, causing one end to rise from within the tube and strike the elbow of the time-governing deity, ringing the bell. The watch and mark mechanisms worked similarly, though watch-balls entered the suspended tube, fell while pressing the mechanism, rose from within the left round column, struck the watch-governing deity's elbow to ring the drum, then rolled into the mark tube and again pressed the initial-mark mechanism, rising from within the right column to strike the mark-governing deity's elbow to ring the gong, finally stopping at the vertical tube below the lotus leaf.

    Where the ball entered, a mechanism was set: initially blocking the watch-ball's path, but as it entered, that path closed while the watch-path opened, and so for each watch. After five watches ended, the latch was withdrawn and the balls released. Below the second mark of each watch, balls fell into the suspended tube, rolled into the lotus leaf, pressed the mark mechanism and stopped. The next mark's ball similarly rolled past, pressed its mechanism and stopped. The tube catching the ball had holes covered and sealed with a latch. When the fifth mark's ball fell and moved the lowest mechanism, a chain connected to successive latches drew all of them, releasing the third mark's balls simultaneously.

    The hour-governing large balls fell into the suspended tube, rolled into the tube attached to the round column, and pressed down the north end of a horizontal timber six feet six inches long, one and one-half inches wide, one and seven-tenths inches thick. At the timber's midpoint stood a short column with a round axle allowing the timber to tilt. At the south end stood a round wooden post like a finger, two feet two inches long, meeting the foot of the hour-announcing deity below. The deity's foot bore a small wheel-axle; as the large ball pressed down the north end, the south end rose to support the deity's foot, lifting them to the middle tier above.

    North of the timber's north end stood a small board that could open and close, connected by iron rope to the hour-governing suspended tube's mechanism-spoon. When the spoon moved, the board opened, releasing the previous ball. The timber's south end lowered while the hour-announcing deity returned to the wheel-face, whereupon the next hour's deity rose in their stead.

    The wheel's rotation mechanism was thus: outside the wheel, a small board was horizontally mounted, about one foot long, with its center excavated four to five inches, upon which a bronze plate was horizontally seated in a gently sloping manner, with one end fitted with an axle allowing opening and closing. The hour-announcing deity's foot initially entered half an inch beneath the bronze plate; ascending, it opened the plate and rose; fully raised, it closed again. When the hour ended and the deity returned to the wheel-face, the foot's iron wheel smoothly rolled down the bronze plate without the slightest pause, and the next hour's deity proceeded likewise.

    All mechanisms were hidden from view; only the formally dressed wooden automata were visible. Such was the general design.
